AB  - Through the development of virtual and remote interaction applications for patients with the Internet of Things, the health sector is greatly accessible and affordable. Physically unstable patients can overcome the difficulty of consulting a doctor regularly by taking advantage of the capabilities of IoT technology. The text describes a conceptual framework of an IoT-based remote health monitoring system. Patients or the elderly can be monitored remotely at home using remote patient monitoring systems which can track their vital signs, including heart rate, temperature, and electrocardiogram remotely using handheld devices. Smart homes can be designed to be able to continuously monitor the health and wellbeing of elderly people through the use of wearables, technology, and communication. Moreover, smart homes may enable elders to live comfortably at home rather than visit high priced and inferior healthcare facilities. Intelligent hybrid systems employ both cloud-based and local components for applications targeting patients under supervision at home. Using the cloud-based component of the model, it is possible to store and analyze big data from a smart environment in order to track chronically ill individuals at home, particularly the elderly. During internet outages or other problems with the cloud system, an application of the model monitors the status of individuals. Physiological, physical, and ambient data are continuously monitored to determine the patient's current wellness using context-aware techniques. © 2022, The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG.
